    <p><strong>Maximizing the Media Machine that is the 2010 International CES</strong><br> 
by Allison Fried</p>
    <p>The 2010 International CES is two months away and buzz is in the air! Exhibitors, attendees and media are filling their appointment books, booking travel and starting the countdown. The world’s largest consumer technology tradeshow is right around the corner, and with more 5,000 media and analysts in attendance, is your company ready?<BR><BR>Press coverage is vital to the marketing strategy of any successful business. CES provides an optimal opportunity to generate media coverage of your company and its products, a value that CES exhibitors continually rank as one of their main reasons for attending the show.<BR><BR>Our media attendees are a "who’s who" of the global press, from the national TV news shows to the top newspapers, radio stations, wire services, trade publications and online outlets, including ABC, the Associated Press, BBC, CBS, CNET, CNBC, LA Times, NBC, New York Times, Wall Street Journal and the Washington Post. &nbsp; <BR><BR>There are plenty of ways for you to reach the media attending the 2010 International CES, and we are here to help. Make sure you check out our <A href="/exhibitors/newsletter/prKit.asp" target=_blank>2010 CES Exhibitor PR Kit</A>. It is an extremely helpful resource full of tips for drafting press releases, creating eye-catching press kits and learning other great PR tactics that grab the media’s attention.&nbsp; <BR><BR>Our media season kicks off on November 10 at the New York Press Preview in New York City. Held in conjunction with the CES Unveiled, this event offers press an insider view of the products that will both turn heads for the upcoming holiday season and make waves in January at CES. The media buzz continues on January 5th at CES Unveiled in Las Vegas, the official press event of International CES. This event draws 800 top-tier press who come for a sneak peak of what will be debuting on the CES show floor that week. If you want reach the media early –these are the places to do it! <BR><BR>Another great way to get in touch with our 5,000 plus media is to create a press kit for our onsite press room, S229 in the South Hall Connector of the LVCC. We are thrilled to announce that this year’s press kit area will be exclusively GREEN! Meaning your company’s press kits MUST be electronic! There are a couple of ways you can do this; you can bring in CD ROMs, USBs or post a URL along with a one page spec sheet. You may also want to consider posting your news online through our <A href="http://www.virtualpressoffice.com/eventsSubmenu.do?page=showPage&showId=53" target=_blank>Online Media Center</A>, hosted by Virtual Press Office and BusinessWire. Remember that press kits are the media’s one-stop resource to find out all they need to know about your company and products.&nbsp;<BR><BR>You should also consider getting your company on the air. If you have a TV-friendly product and are interested in having it shown on-air, contact Jim Barry at <A href="mailto:bosjim@comcast.net">bosjim@comcast.net</A> and send a brief description of your product for consideration.<BR><BR>Download and use the <A href="/exhibitors/pr/default.asp" target=_blank>CES pre-registered media list</A> (available November 4, 2009). The pre-registered media list contains contact information for all media and analysts that have registered for the 2010 International CES. It is the perfect way to target select media that are interested in covering your company’s product category.<BR><BR>And yes there is still time for you to schedule a press event. Companies who have major news to announce are encouraged to hold a press conference at CES. Each exhibitor is eligible to reserve one of our CES press conference rooms for free on a first come first serve basis. If you would like to take advantage of this option, please fill out our <A href="http://www.cesweb.org/docs/PressConf_Form.pdf" target=_blank>Press Conference Reservation Form</A> and fax it into me ASAP.&nbsp;<BR><BR>Tell your story to the local media. To gain more regional coverage, participate in the <A href="http://www.cesweb.org/docs/RegionalMedia.pdf" target=_blank>CES Regional Media Outreach Campaign</A> and submit a quote from a company executive to be included in a press release sent to the media in your area.<BR><BR>Finally, social media will play a major role in this year's show, and it is important to listen to what is being said about your company on blogs, Twitter, Facebook, web portals, photo/video networks, etc. <A href="http://eventbuzz.vnewscenter.com/" target=_blank>EventBuzz</A> provides insight into the volume of content and also the sentiment or tone of the "buzz" you are creating before, during and after the event. <BR><BR>These are just a few helpful hints for reaching the CES media machine and maximizing your company’s media exposure at the 2010 International CES. Please feel free to contact me directly with any PR questions: <A href="mailto:afried@CE.org">afried@CE.org</A>. <BR></p>
